         <h1>Ronald Rivlin, 90, Expert on Properties of Rubber </h1>
           <div class="row">
               <div class="col-md-10">
 					<p class="text-left">
<blue>1</blue>Ronald S. Rivlin , an applied mathematician who conducted pioneering studies of the elastic properties of rubber and other materials and developed formulas to explain their behavior , died on Oct. 4 at his home in Palo Alto , Calif . <br><blue>2</blue>He was 90 . <br><blue>3</blue>His death was confirmed by his family . <br><blue>4</blue>Dr. Rivlin began his work in the 1940 's , using tools of theoretical physics to investigate the properties of vulcanized rubber . <br><blue>5</blue>He and others experimented with the effects of various loads in deforming rubber and contributed to a field known as finite elasticity theory , which looks at how materials behave during elastic deformation . <br><blue>6</blue>The work has had subsequent applications in materials engineering . <br><blue>7</blue>Daniel D. Joseph , a professor of aerospace engineering and mechanics at the University of Minnesota , said Dr. Rivlin helped describe how rubber behaved under stress and strain and how it fractured . <br><blue>8</blue>Later , Dr. Rivlin studied the behavior of fluids under different forces . <br><blue>9</blue>He and others developed equations to express the behavior of fluids and other complex materials that fall under the field of rheology . <br><blue>10</blue>In collaboration with other scientists , he developed equations known as Reiner-Rivlin and Rivlin-Ericksen for fluids , and the Mooney-Rivlin equation for incompressible solids , materials that can be deformed but do not change in volume . <br><blue>11</blue>All three equations are used to explain the behaviors of materials . <br><blue>12</blue>Ronald Samuel Rivlin was born in London . <br><blue>13</blue>He received an undergraduate degree in physics and mathematics from St. John 's College at Cambridge in 1937 . <br><blue>14</blue>He earned his doctorate from Cambridge in 1952 . <br><blue>15</blue>Dr. Rivlin worked as a physicist for the British Rubber Producers Research Association before being named superintendent of research for the association from 1950 to 1953 . <br><blue>16</blue>He was then appointed a professor of applied mathematics at Brown University , where he became chairman of the division of applied mathematics , and taught there until 1967 . <br><blue>17</blue>Dr. Rivlin became a United States citizen in 1955 . <br><blue>18</blue>He was a member of the National Academy of Engineering and the American Academy of Arts and Sciences . <br><blue>19</blue>From 1967 to 1980 , he was director of the Center for the Application of Mathematics at Lehigh University in Bethlehem , Pa. , where he was also a professor of mathematics and mechanics . <br><blue>20</blue>His wife of 57 years , the former Violet LoRusso , survives him . <br><hr><br><blue>1(2)</blue>: <m_str>the association</m_str> (15_21) 	<m_str>the British Rubber Producers Research Association</m_str> (15_8) 	<br><blue>2(2)</blue>: <m_str>The work</m_str> (6_1) 	<m_str>his work</m_str> (4_4) 	<br><blue>3(1)</blue>: <m_str>Bethlehem</m_str> (19_21) 	<br><blue>4(2)</blue>: <m_str>formulas</m_str> (1_23) 	<m_str>their</m_str> (1_26) 	<br><blue>5(24)</blue>: <m_str>Dr. Rivlin</m_str> (15_1) 	<m_str>Dr. Rivlin</m_str> (4_1) 	<m_str>his</m_str> (4_4) 	<m_str>he</m_str> (19_6) 	<m_str>Dr. Rivlin</m_str> (7_19) 	<m_str>Dr. Rivlin</m_str> (8_3) 	<m_str>Ronald Samuel Rivlin</m_str> (12_1) 	<m_str>He</m_str> (16_1) 	<m_str>His</m_str> (20_1) 	<m_str>He</m_str> (5_1) 	<m_str>He</m_str> (9_1) 	<m_str>he</m_str> (19_26) 	<m_str>He</m_str> (13_1) 	<m_str>he</m_str> (16_15) 	<m_str>him</m_str> (20_13) 	<m_str>He</m_str> (2_1) 	<m_str>Dr. Rivlin</m_str> (17_1) 	<m_str>He</m_str> (14_1) 	<m_str>he</m_str> (10_7) 	<m_str>his</m_str> (14_3) 	<m_str>his</m_str> (1_34) 	<m_str>He</m_str> (18_1) 	<m_str>His</m_str> (3_1) 	<m_str>his</m_str> (3_6) 	<br><blue>6(4)</blue>: <m_str>rubber</m_str> (5_13) 	<m_str>it</m_str> (7_32) 	<m_str>rubber</m_str> (4_22) 	<m_str>rubber</m_str> (7_24) 	<hr><br> gender:male	ethnicity:european<br